			<ns0:name>dmichael@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/dmichael@google.com/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">sine_synth was the cause of the horrible sound.  It was taking the result of sin (which of course ranges from -1 to 1) and scaling it to std::numeric_limits&lt;uint16_t&gt;::max();  so the wave had twice the amplitude it should have, and was half the time doing an unsafe conversion from a negative double to a uint16_t.  Furthermore, the Chrome implementation apparently expects signed 16-bit ints, not unsigned.  So that may also have contributed to the problem.

I'm still tweaking the code to see if I can make it more readable.  I'll upload a CL in a bit.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2010-12-23T16:49:47.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2010-12-23T16:49:47.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:updates /><ns0:title>Comment 12 by dmichael@google.com</ns0:title><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/issues/detail?id=904#c12" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><ns0:link href="https://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/904/comments/full/12" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /></ns0:entry>